The position property in CSS controls how an element is positioned on a webpage. It works together with the properties top, right, bottom, and left.

There are 5 main values for the position property:

1. static (Default)
Every HTML element is position: static by default.
Elements appear in the normal document flow.
top, left, right, and bottom do not work.
Example
<div class="box">Static Box</div>
.box {
    position: static;
    background: lightblue;
    width: 150px;
    height: 100px;
}

Output:

Normal Flow
----------------
| Static Box   |
----------------
2. relative

The element stays in its normal position, but you can move it using top, left, right, or bottom.

The original space is still reserved.

Example
<div class="box">Relative Box</div>
.box {
    position: relative;
    top: 20px;
    left: 30px;
    background: orange;
    width: 150px;
    height: 100px;
}

Original Position:

[X]

After moving:

Original Space
[X]

Moved Box
        [X]

Notice:

The box moves.
The original space remains empty.
3. absolute

The element is removed from the normal flow.

It is positioned relative to the nearest ancestor with a position other than static (relative, absolute, fixed, or sticky). If none exists, it is positioned relative to the page (<body>/viewport).

Example
<div class="container">
    <div class="box">Absolute</div>
</div>
.container {
    position: relative;
    width: 300px;
    height: 200px;
    background: lightgray;
}

.box {
    position: absolute;
    top: 20px;
    right: 20px;
    width: 80px;
    height: 80px;
    background: red;
}

Visualization:

------------------------
|                      |
|                [Box] |
|                      |
|                      |
------------------------

The red box is positioned relative to the container.

4. fixed

The element stays fixed relative to the browser window.

Even when you scroll, it stays in the same position.

Example
button {
    position: fixed;
    bottom: 20px;
    right: 20px;
}

Result:

------------------------
|                      |
|                      |
|                      |
|                 Btn  |
------------------------

Scroll the page:

------------------------
|                      |
|                      |
|                      |
|                 Btn  |
------------------------

The button never moves.

Common uses:

Chat icon
Back to Top button
Floating action button
5. sticky

Acts like relative until a specified scroll position is reached, then behaves like fixed.

Example
header {
    position: sticky;
    top: 0;
}

Initially:

Header
Content
Content

After scrolling:

Header (sticks here)
---------------------
Content
Content

Common uses:

Navigation bars
Table headers
Difference Between Relative and Absolute
Relative	Absolute
Stays in normal flow	Removed from normal flow
Original space remains	No original space
Moves from its original position	Moves relative to nearest positioned parent
Used for small adjustments	Used for precise positioning
Difference Between Fixed and Sticky
Fixed	Sticky
Always fixed to the viewport	Becomes fixed only after scrolling to a threshold
Doesn't move while scrolling	Scrolls normally until it reaches the specified position
Uses the browser viewport	Depends on its scroll container
Position Hierarchy Example
<div class="parent">
    Parent
    <div class="child">
        Child
    </div>
</div>
.parent {
    position: relative;
    width: 300px;
    height: 200px;
    background: lightgray;
}

.child {
    position: absolute;
    top: 30px;
    left: 50px;
    width: 100px;
    height: 60px;
    background: tomato;
}

Here:

.parent is the reference because it has position: relative.
.child is positioned 30px from the top and 50px from the left of the parent.
Quick Summary
Position	In Normal Flow?	Moves Relative To	Scroll Behavior
static	✅ Yes	Normal flow	Scrolls normally
relative	✅ Yes	Its original position	Scrolls normally
absolute	❌ No	Nearest positioned ancestor	Scrolls normally
fixed	❌ No	Browser viewport	Stays fixed
sticky	✅ Initially	Scroll container/viewport after threshold	Sticks after reaching the specified offset
Interview Questions
What is the default value of the position property?
Answer: static
Which position value removes an element from the normal document flow?
Answer: absolute and fixed
Why is position: relative commonly applied to a parent of an absolutely positioned element?
Answer: It creates the positioning context, so the child is positioned relative to the parent instead of the page.
What is the difference between fixed and sticky?
Answer: fixed is always attached to the viewport, while sticky behaves like relative until the scroll reaches the specified offset, then it sticks.
Do top, left, right, and bottom work with position: static?
Answer: No. They only work with positioned elements (relative, absolute, fixed, or sticky).
